nt><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehouseloungegeneraldiscussion.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=22637.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Real Life&gt;EQ</span><hr size=1> Well...the thing is...EQ *can* be a drug to some people.  It's like drinking...some people drink, and become addicted, become alcoholics.  Some drink and never develop an addiction to it. <br>
<br>
I play all the time, I'd definitely consider myself an addict, personally.  I'm a *functional* addict, I have a RL, and enjoy it thoroughly, but addicted, nevertheless.  I know people that it never affects their real life negatively, and I know a few people who have given up *everything* for the free time to feed their addiction.  I know a person who quit his job and depends on his parents to support him with money (and this guy isn't young, or a teenager either, he's in his 30's) because he literally almost never leaves the house anymore, lost his girlfriend as well as all his RL friends because of it, and gained *alot* of weight, whereas pre-EQ, he was a pretty fit and healthy person as well as popular, he had alot of good friends irl who cared about him, and he used to really enjoy going out dancing, as well as a really good job...he does and has none of those things anymore...he traded them all for several 50+ characters.<br>
<br>
It's not always negative.   In my case, I met the man I love  and now live with irl in this game.  I moved across the country to a city I knew no one but him in...and have quite a few friends here now...I met them playing EQ as well, once a month or so we all get together and go hang out at a local bar, play pool and shoot the breeze till the place closes up, and our gatherings get bigger every month, think the last one we had upwards of 15 EQ friends come hang with us.  My rl bf is trying to help one of his EQ friends who lives in the area get a job, passed his resume to his boss *crosses her fingers*.  <br>
<br>
At times I've gone thru some pretty rough things irl, and had a few EQ friends really help me pull thru with love and support, and understanding.  I had a very dear friend a while back suffering from severe depression, and can remember a very long draining evening talking him down from a suicide attempt and making sure he didnt log off...not an easy trick when you're in Chicago and he's in Australia.  I kept him online all night, till our guildleader at the time logged on, another of our very good friends, and had him call him, from California to Oz...6 hours later, we had gotten him out of it, and had his father taking him in the morning to seek help for his depression.<br>
<br>
*shakes head and sighs*  Guess the point of my rambling is this...EQ is like anything else...it can be alot of fun and a positive experience...but too much most definitely can be a bad thing.  Balance in all things.  Would I rather do this then go out and spend alot of money I don't have at a bar all night?  Definitely.  Would I rather do this than maintain a RL relationship, a job, and a healthy lifestyle?  Most definitely not.<br>
<br>
And Neuro, I urge you to please talk to someone you trust, if not a rl person, than at least an EQ friend who can urge you to get help.  I urge you to talk to your parents, or someone at school and seek help...teen years can be rough, I know...but there's so much worth living for...just have to get thru the bad patches to see it.<br>
<br>
